	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Being such an avid CV3 fan, I of course disagree with this guy's point of view. I don't know what he thinks is better about CV1 than CV3. CV3 is a lot like CV1, except you get to enter passwords to pick up from where you left off, there's a ton more levels, options, and power-ups... The music's better, the graphics are better... The environments are more interesting... It's far less linear... True, it's more rewarding when you beat the 2 ridiculously hard bosses in CV1 (Frankenstein and Death), but in CV3 you get annoyed a lot less. Plus, there are bosses later on that are equally challenging, just not crappy and cheap.
<br />
<br />I also think this has been quite dissected by the writer, to the point where I wouldn't have even really thought about some of these things. Yeah, it's hard to avoid getting hit by the boss once. Yeah the level doesn't have many platforms in this one spot. Yeah, there are fleamen instead of skeletons in that other spot. Can we get over it?
<br />
<br />And really, do we need the big thesis for your master's degree in gaming psychology in the beginning? I didn't expect to read 8 paragraphs about human behavior, evolution, and the meaning of life in a frickin' review of Dracula's Curse.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


